			<div style="clear: both"></div>	<div>
		<ol id="comment-list-wrapper" class="commentlist commentlist-partial-hidden">
				<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-1522023">
				<div id="div-comment-1522023" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/943cb24b4858a7847b279219d9e1a3d9?s=32&#038;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&#038;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn">Zariji Dela Rosa</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/american-crime-season-2-john-ridley-1201554723/#comment-list-wrapper">
			August 1, 2015 at 11:41 am</a>		</div>

		<p>Can&#8217;t wait to see the new season as I know it will continue  to be a of rich storytelling expereince in the legacy of John Ridley commentary. The only thing I hope does not confuse the audience is the roles of the principal and the basketball coach. Both Huffman and Hutton were brilliant in their stand alone roles last season. They were so memorable that it may be difficult for audiences to re-set their minds to accepting new characters, regardless of their extraordinary performances. I am delighted that Ridley is building an ensemble of actors, like Shakespeare, that roll from one play to the next. But TV audiences have become accustom to &#8216;tuning in&#8217; to last season&#8217;s cliff-hangers, and Hutton&#8217;s resurrection alone may be difficult for some to overcome. Look forward to seeing nonetheless! Congrats!</p>

		<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2015/tv/news/american-crime-season-2-john-ridley-1201554723/?replytocom=1522023#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "div-comment-1522023", "1522023", "respond", "1201554723" )' aria-label='Reply to Zariji Dela Rosa'>Reply</a></div>
				</div>
		</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		</ol>
